# Fluff Date: 2026-02-28 17:47:08
overview:<p>The Corvis is a 40-ton medium BattleMech introduced in the mid-twenty-ninth century by Clan Hell's Horses at the Niles Industriplex Alpha facility. The design drew on the Star League Mercury BattleMech's semi-modular weapon port concept, applying early modular technology to create a chassis that could swap primary armament systems in the field. Though frequently dismissed as underpowered for its weight class and slow compared to other Clan mediums, the Corvis's modular weapons and jump capability have made it a practical support platform for the combined-arms operations that define Hell's Horses military doctrine. Only the Horses continue to manufacture the design at Niles, where it fills garrison and second-line roles alongside conventional vehicles and infantry formations.</p>

capabilities:<p>Built on a Model MH-24 endo steel chassis with seven tons of Compound H17 ferro-fibrous armor, the Corvis uses a 160-rated fusion engine that limits its top speed to just 65 km/h, making it one of the slowest medium BattleMechs in any Clan arsenal. Four Model KT jump jet boosters compensate for this lack of speed, providing a 120-meter jump range that proves valuable in restrictive terrain such as urban environments and dense forests where raw speed matters less than vertical mobility.</p><p>The Corvis's semi-modular weapon ports allow field technicians to swap primary armament systems without the full pod reconfiguration capability of a true OmniMech. While this modularity is limited compared to later designs, it provides more flexibility than a standard BattleMech and allows garrison commanders to tailor loadouts to expected threats. The primary limitation remains the chassis's modest tonnage budget, which constrains both armor protection and weapons payload relative to more modern Clan medium designs.</p>

deployment:<p>The standard Corvis mounts a Type DL Ultra AC/10 as its primary weapon, backed by a pair of Series 14a medium pulse lasers. This armament enables effective medium to short range engagements, with abundant ammunition stores allowing extended operations without resupply. The configuration is well suited to the garrison and combined-arms support duties typically assigned to Corvis pilots.</p>

history:<p>The Corvis was developed by Clan Hell's Horses in the mid-twenty-ninth century at Niles Industriplex Alpha. Drawing on the Star League Mercury BattleMech's semi-modular weapon port concept, the Corvis represented an early experiment in modular 'Mech design that would have far-reaching consequences for Clan warfare.</p><p>Clan technicians expanded on the Corvis's modular design philosophy to create the Omni-Corvis prototype OmniMech in 2921. This experimental design debuted during the fateful Battle of Tokasha, where Clan Ghost Bear seized control of the planet and its manufacturing facilities. In retaliation for Khan Kilbourne Jorgensson's death, Ghost Bear released the Omni-Corvis blueprints on the Chatterweb, scattering the design across Clan space. Only Clan Snow Raven pursued the plans further, ultimately refining them into the Stormcrow -- one of the most successful OmniMechs in Clan history -- by 2930.</p><p>Despite the Stormcrow's overwhelming success, Clan Hell's Horses continued manufacturing the Corvis at Niles. Often deployed as support for conventional troops such as combat vehicles and infantry, the original design found a lasting niche in combined-arms operations that fit perfectly with the Horses' military doctrine. By the thirty-first century, no other Clan maintained production of this largely obsolete but historically significant design.</p>

